      "writtenOn": "2022-01-06T19:38:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This function up to this point is almost the same as minijail_getenv, so it makes sense to pull the shared code out to in internal helper function that returns the index of the matching **envp entry or -1. It could possibly be used in setenv as well.",
      "revId": "0f0427f55bf161721dddb4d2fe92435f1bdbe92a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8ae2e04d_612c86ca",
        "filename": "util.c",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 633,
      "author": {
        "id": 1628636
      },
      "writtenOn": "2022-01-07T10:53:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Done, I named it \"getenv_index\" and declared it as static in util.c, as I don\u0027t expect it to be of any use outside of this file.\nIt is used by the 2 new utility funcs added by this change, and I also integrated it in minijail_setenv. Note that for this one, we still need to count the number of vars in the env array, which is not handled by getenv_index (the code complexity would roughly double if it had to optionally implement this feature, which is only required by minijail_setenv, so it defeats our original purpose of simplifying the code). The code is simpler this way, the only drawback being that in minijail_setenv, a portion of the env array will be walked through in getenv_index, then we walk through the entire array again in minijail_setenv to get its size. I think this is a reasonable compromise between code clarity vs execution speed (we\u0027re probably talking microseconds here).",
      "parentUuid": "08df279d_99546d78",
      "revId": "0f0427f55bf161721dddb4d2fe92435f1bdbe92a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    }
